## 4. Real World Case Study — Personal Experience

During my IT Systems Administrator internship at Addon Engineering
Solutions (September 2024 to February 2025), my wife became the
victim of an online financial scam.

The attack used classic social engineering techniques:
- Created a false sense of urgency
- Impersonated a legitimate platform or contact
- Exploited trust and digital unfamiliarity
- Resulted in financial loss

As an IT professional, I understood the mechanics of what had happened.
But understanding it technically did not mean I had been able to
protect the person closest to me from becoming a victim. That gap
between technical knowledge and practical protection felt personally
unacceptable.

This experience highlighted several realities about Nepal's
cybersecurity landscape:

1. Technical knowledge alone is insufficient — awareness education
   is equally critical
2. Ordinary people with no technical background are extremely
   vulnerable to well-crafted social engineering
3. Digital payment platforms in Nepal — while convenient — have
   created new attack surfaces that many users do not understand
4. The human element of security cannot be addressed through
   technology alone

This personal experience is the direct origin of my commitment to
cybersecurity specialisation and my goal of contributing to
cybersecurity awareness and education in Nepal upon completing
the Master of Information Technology at the University of Waikato.

